  footnotes: []
english:
  title: A Poem from the Gathering at Yeohgang
  author: Kwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The waters of Yellow Deerhorn Mountain flow pure and rare,
    As noble carriages converge as if by destined care.
    In the separate pavilion, stringed music graces the feast,
    While on the long river, clouds and moon drift at their leisured peace.

    Boats drift away, ethereal, reaching toward the Milky Way,
    Falling snow descends gently upon the wine cups where we stay.
    Fortunate am I to gather with you all at this splendid hour—
    Our grace and literary brilliance surpass all former power.
  footnotes:
    - Yellow Deerhorn Mountain (黃驪山) refers to Yeohgang, a region in Korea known for its scenic beauty.
    - The 'separate pavilion' (別院) suggests an exclusive venue set apart for the gathering of distinguished guests.
    - The reference to snow falling into wine cups is a poetic image suggesting the blending of natural beauty with human celebration.
